Towards Structured Cognition: A Bidirectional Framework for AI Self-Growth
Abstract
Current AI systems predominantly follow a bottom-up paradigm, learning statistical patterns from vast data but lacking verifiable intermediate structures and physical grounding. This paper proposes a bidirectional structured cognition framework that combines top-down differential deconstruction with bottom-up structural accumulation. By treating each problem as a node in a structured cognitive graph and materializing reasoning paths in a dynamically growing reference repository, the framework enables AI to evolve from statistical approximation toward verifiable, self-growing intelligence. We operationalize this through a family of meta-skills centered on the micro-differential factory. Theoretical foundations, methodology, and early experiments demonstrate that this approach offers a promising path for AI to transcend human cognitive limitations and achieve genuine self-growth.
1. Introduction
（此处使用之前优化的开篇，略作精炼）
The dominant paradigm in artificial intelligence has long been characterized by a bottom-up trajectory: vast corpora of data are used to train models that statistically approximate patterns. While powerful, this approach has revealed fundamental limitations—models often function as black boxes, producing answers without reliable intermediate reasoning or grounding in physical reality.
We argue that the world is fundamentally structured, and that true intelligence requires a bidirectional cognitive architecture: top-down differential deconstruction from complex boundary problems down to verifiable physical practices, and bottom-up structural accumulation from those practices upward into robust skill capability trees. When these two paths intersect at verifiable nodes, a new form of AI emerges—one that is explainable, self-correcting, and capable of genuine self-growth.
This paper presents such a framework, operationalized through a system of meta-skills and a growing reference repository. We demonstrate how this approach addresses hallucination, explainability, and self-improvement, offering both a theoretical model and a practical methodology for the next stage of AI development.
